 	<h1 class="page">Biological Mimicry</h1>

 	<h2>Overview</h2>
 	<p>Mimicry in nature refers to the ability of certain organisms to appear as a different manner of creature, whether it be for defense, reproduction, or ambush tactics. Many animals have been observed to mimic others, but the tactic is not unheard of in plants as well, and one could argue it has even been observed in microorganisms.</p>
 	<h2>Defensive mimicry</h2>
 	<p>Defensive mimicry is probably the most well-known form of mimicry observed in animals, defined as any appearance or behavior that evolved to seem like a different kind of animal (or inanimate object) towards the purpose of dissuading predators, either by appearing to be excessively dangerous, or as a non-food item that is not worth attacking.</p>
 	<p>One of the most obvious forms of defensive mimicry is for an animal to disguise itself as a more predatory, poisonous, or otherwise dangerous animal, essentially using a false threat to deter real threats to themselves. This can be seen in many insect species, who love to imitate ants and/or vespids, those being the most threatening and least targetable forms of insect out there. Mimics of this type have an upper limit to their population, however- they cannot exceed the number of the more dangerous species that they imitate, lest predators figure out that most of the creatures of that appearance are harmless, and start to take the risk of attacking even the more dangerous species, since their chances of scoring a harmless mimic are higher.</p>
 	<p>Although it is often a specific species that is imitated, sometimes mimicry can work off of little more than vibes. Many moths and butterflies, for instance, famously have eye patterns on their wings. These are a rather lazy attempt at mimicry, and only really work if the full body of the moth/butterfly is obscured, but that's the way they evolved, so it must do something to ward of predators.</p>
 	<p>Another school of mimicry is for dangerous animals to appear similar to other dangerous animals. This may not seem like a huge benefit, at first- if the animal is already dangerous, why would it need to disguise itself as a similarly dangerous species? The answer is that this type of mimic is one of the few that benefits both species, making predators less likely to attack either one. The best example of this is the visual similarities between wasps, bees, and hornets.</p>
 	<p>Imagine, if you will, a scenario where bees look completely different from wasps. A predator attacks a bee hive, doing serious damage to the hive, but at a cost to themselves, leaning never to attack bees again. It then finds a wasp hive, and since they do not resemble each other, it decides to attack the wasps as well, killing many of their number. The same would be true if it attacked the wasps first, then the bees. But since bees and wasps have such close visual similarities, a predator who has attacked bees and learned that they are dangerous will then also be conditioned to avoid wasps, and vice versa, since it can’t really tell them apart. Through this mutual mimicry, both bees and wasps are less likely to be targeted, forming a visual language of black and yellow meaning danger. This language has been exploited by non-venomous insects, however, so it isn’t all positives.</p>
 	<div>
		<p>Bonus list of bugs that mimic wasps:</p>
 		<ul class="grid">
 			<li>Hoverfly</li>
 			<li>Wasp Beetle</li>
 			<li>Mydas Fly</li>
 			<li><em>Pseudosphex laticincta</em> (Moth)</li>
 		</ul>
 	</div>
 	<p>There is one more type of defensive mimicry, and it is likely the rarest and least understandable. In uncommon cases, an extremely dangerous animal might seek to mimic a less dangerous one. This type of imitation would usually be seen in offensive mimicry, but these animals use it for defense. One would think this would be counterproductive; why pretend to be have less defenses than you actually do, when you don’t want to be attacked? The answer can be found in the example of the deadly coral snake, which mimics another much less venomous snake. The reason for this is that the coral snake is too lethal for its own good: any attack on a coral snake is likely to end in death for the attacker, meaning they never learn to avoid coral snakes and the snakes keep being attacked. While they are adept at killing their attacker, they also may be heavily injured or killed in the process, so they need a deterrence method to keep threats away. Enter the less venomous species, who rarely ever kills their attacker, yet inflicts enough pain with their venom that the predator is unlikely to attack that species again. By mimicking this less lethal snake, the coral snake can reap the benefits of the predator’s learned aversion to snakes of that appearance, and can avoid being attacked altogether, which is more effective for survival than simply killing the attacker.</p>
 	<h2>Aggressive mimicry</h2>
 	<p>While some animals foolishly expend energy trying to chase down food, more intelligent creatures make the victims come to them. Aggressive mimicry, as the name implies, is the exact opposite of defensive mimicry. Aggressive mimics assume the guise of something harmless and/or appetizing, drawing in prey (or sometimes hosts) to their own doom.</p>
 	<div><img src="images/orchid_mantis.jpg" alt="An orchid mantis."></div>
 	<p>Many forms of aggressive mimicry see a predator disguise itself as either a food source, or a symbiote of the target. In either case, the prey is drawn toward the desirable mimicry, where it is then ambushed and eaten, or partially eaten, by the mimic. One great example of this behavior is the orchid mantis, who goes above and beyond to not only mimic one food source, but two. The more obvious mimicry, for which it is named, is the resemblance to part of an orchid flower. The mantis attaches itself to a flower and pretends to be part of it, even swaying to simulate a breeze, drawing smaller insects toward it with hopes of nectar. But the mantis has a second trick up its sleeve: a small black dot on its abdomen, which predatory insects can mistake for a small fly that has landed on the flower. When an insect large enough to be a full meal lands within reach, there is not much it can do against the claws of the mantis.</p>
 	<img src="images/spider_tail.jpg" alt="A spider-tailed viper.">
 	<p>The orchid mantis uses its whole body to mimic a part of a flower, but some animals go the opposite direction: the spider-tailed horned viper is too large to reasonably masquerade as the prey of its prey, so it thinks smaller. Staying perfectly still with its main body, the viper uses camouflage to become virtually invisible from the air. It then starts moving the tip of its tail periodically, imitating the start-stop movement of an insect. The tip of the tail is uniquely developed with elongated scales resembling arthropod legs and a juicy-looking bulb at the end. This display is irresistible to many birds that see it from overhead, and they will swoop down to eat what they think is a small bug. When the viper strikes, it is as if the ground itself came to life, discarding its motionless camouflage for a lightning strike on the bird, filling it up with cell-destroying venom.</p>
 	<p>The two forces that drive most organisms are food and reproduction. Many ambush mimics appear as the food of their victim, but some take the other route of desire. One species of firefly more vicious than the rest has developed a flashing signal almost indistinguishable from the mating display of other species’ females, luring in males of those species, who are then killed. Next time you stay up at night watching the fireflies, know that some of those flashes could have a more sinister purpose than the rest.</p>
 	<div><img src="images/parasite_eyes.jpg" alt="A parasitized snail."></div>
 	<p>Predatory mimics may pretend to be food, but they have no intention of being eaten. But parasites will make themselves as appetizing as possible specifically to be eaten by their favored host. One memorable flatworm has two host species, songbirds and snails. In order to travel between hosts and complete their life cycle, the flatworm must make the songbird eat a snail host, which poses a challenge, since snails are not the bird’s usual food source. The worm meets this challenge in a disgusting way, as it moves to the eye stalk of the snail, making the stalk much more colorful, as well as making it pulse, resembling an irresistible caterpillar delight, a delicacy for songbirds. The eyestalk is gobbled up, and the flatworm is able to mature inside the body of the songbird, until its eggs are dropped in the bird’s feces to infect more snails below.</p>
 	<h2>Reproductive mimicry</h2>
 	<p>Not all mimicry is quite so combative as killing or being killed. Some organisms use instead use trickery to spread their genes, fooling other creatures into helping them breed. This technique is found among several lazy orchids, who mimic nectar-giving flowers to attract pollinators, covering them in pollen without needing to give out any nectar. This saves them the energy cost of making said nectar, but like the vespid mimics, there is an upper limit on their population: too many frauds, and the pollinators will stop visiting flowers that look like that at all.</p>
 	<div><img src="images/mirror_orchid.jpg" alt="A mirror orchid."></div>
 	<p>Not all orchids are so lazy as to mimic other flowers- one species goes beyond the call of duty to deceive bugs, taking the shape (as well as the smell) of a female wasp. Males will spot the flower and immediately begin trying to mate with it, getting themselves covered in pollen and accomplishing nothing for their own species. They will then repeat this mistake with a different flower, becoming an unwitting pollinator for the flower mimic.</p>
 	<p>Plants are prolific in the art of reproductive mimicry, but they by no means have a monopoly. Some animals seek not to fool other species, but rivals within their own. The cuttlefish is a shining example of this. When it comes time to mate, large male cuttlefish will fight each other over the less common females, even going so far as to flush the sperm of other males out of the female’s egg sack. But not all males are large enough to compete directly, so some employ a more insidious means of competition. Using their smaller size to their advantage, they change color to imitate a female cuttlefish, allowing them to swim past larger males without conflict, mating with the females behind their backs.</p>
